<br>
Raid Guidelines The raid you plan should be for your level or lower. <br>
<br>
<br>
Ensure attendance by advertising your raid (Guild MOTD, News section, Calendar and forum) and planning far enough in advance for word to get around. <br>
<br>
<br>
Plan only one raid at a time. This reduces confusion and allows others a chance to plan raids. You can plan multiple raids and announce them, however they should be far enough apart to allow others to squeeze in their needs. <br>
<br>
<br>
Have clear goals and announce the goals to the raiding party so that everyone is on the same page. <br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Announce how to handle loot prior to raid. Need before greed, alpha, first loot first serve, or magic dice rolling.</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> <br>
<br>
<br>
Create chat channel with a name easy to spell or know (Example: /join Brewer {gnoll brewer raid in Blackburrow}) <br>
<br>
<br>
Choose group leaders who you know will conduct themselves well with you, or that you know personally <br>
<br>
<br>
Establish &quot;safe spots&quot; when moving to the raid area. Healers need to med to keep their mana. Oh yea, no mana, no heal. Same with other casters. <br>
<br>
<br>
Make sure everyone knows not to pass you unless running to next safe spot, and stand where people shouldn't pass. <br>
<br>
<br>
Know the area very well before you get there. Study maps on eqatlas and print them out. If possible, scope out the area before the raid. <br>
<br>
<br>
Explain politely how to use necessary things such as /assist and not to break mez to people who don't understand. Try to be patient with people who are following the rules and trying. <br>
<br>
<br>
You have the option to remove people from the raid who are transgressing or going against your commands in the raid. <br>
<br>
<br>
You are not required to wait for people who are late nor send them guides. This choice is at your discretion. <br>
